task.summary: 1) The database will no longer work with the old client. 2) The database now has some (not all) of the data it needs to have in it. 3) The query parser is under way. It recieves the json and itterates the nodes, but doesn't check if it has the right node yet. 4) There is no capicity to extand the graph: IE: we know what color blankets the bed CAN have, but cannot spawn an instance with only one color! 5) I'm not sure how the node re-use vs create new node situation will shake out. What if two nodes are the same now, but they diverge later? 6) The edges are still not stored as tables against time.

The database now stores data "correctly". It has made me realize I need to confront "is a" and node re-use in general.
The query system is written and totally un-tested. I'm fixing that now.
Fixed a bug where I copied text from google docs into a comment. The ' in the google doc was not ascii and gave pypy a heart attack.
Tweaked main so it compiles. Still does nothing useful, per-se.
Debugging full nouns. Fixed frank -> fred.
Database queries somehow. Somehow work. It's ugly though, so I'm about to refactor half of it away.
The database should now work correctly. Going to test a few more queries now to be sure.
Commented lightly. Will comment more heavily soon.
